<p>Late one evening 55 years ago, in the winter of 1966, an Irish American =
teenager named Gwen Taylor climbed through the window of her family=E2=80=
=99s house in Coalinga, a small town in California=E2=80=99s San Joaquin Va=
lley, and, flipping up the kickstand on a bicycle parked outside, pedaled b=
y moonlight through the vineyards of this farming region, and across Inters=
tate 5 to a town called Huron.</p>
<p>No more than 15 miles separated two places that were, in crucial ways, u=
niverses apart. As late as the 1960s, the inhabitants of Coalinga, a onetim=
e railway coaling station, were primarily Caucasian, whereas Huron was popu=
lated largely by Mexican Americans or Mexican migrants who regularly risked=
 the illegal border crossing in search of seasonal work harvesting the worl=
d=E2=80=99s tomatoes, melons, sugar beets, grapes and asparagus.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CMy mother hates when I tell this story,=E2=80=9D designer Willy=
 Chavarria said over a glass of chilled white wine on a recent rainy evenin=
g, referring to his origins as the son of a white girl from a =E2=80=9Csund=
own town,=E2=80=9D where it was once thought unsafe for those with brown sk=
in to be seen after nightfall, and of William Robles Chavarria, a migrant w=
orker himself and an activist whose mother on occasion fed Cesar Chavez, th=
e legendary civil rights activist and co-founder of the National Farm Worke=
rs Association, at her kitchen table.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CMy parents met in high school, which began to be integrated onl=
y after the civil rights movement,=E2=80=9D Chavarria, 54, said. =E2=80=9CS=
he used to sneak out of the house and ride to Huron through the crop fields=
 to see my father.=E2=80=9D And then unexpectedly, in July 1967, =E2=80=9Cl=
ittle Willy came along.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>In order to understand Willy Chavarria and his decadeslong rise through =
the ranks of fashion, first as a journeyman designer for mass-market labels=
 like Joe Boxer, Ralph Lauren and American Eagle to the founding in 2015 of=
 a critically lauded indie label and his surprise hire early this year as a=
 senior vice president at Calvin Klein, it helps to understand his origins.=
</p>
<p>A queer man of mixed race, a son of working-class folk, Chavarria may be=
 the most highly placed Latino currently at work on the creative end of the=
 American fashion industry. Though not yet a household name, he soon should=
 be, say industry experts familiar with Chavarria=E2=80=99s outsize gifts a=
nd unusual career.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s obviously a huge talent,=E2=80=9D Karla Martinez d=
e Salas, the editor of Vogue Mexico, said recently. =E2=80=9CBut it=E2=80=
=99s in terms of representation that his appointment is an even a bigger de=
al.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>Mexican American herself, Martinez related a story of growing up in El P=
aso, Texas, where she passed a large part of her childhood trying to =E2=80=
=9Cfit into=E2=80=9D an Anglo-dominated culture, one that expected people l=
ike her to alter themselves to conform to Eurocentric beauty ideals. =E2=80=
=9CGrowing up a slightly dark-skinned kid, a Latina, in the U.S., there was=
 nothing speaking to us,=E2=80=9D she said.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CAnd before Oscar, Narciso and Carolina came along, there was no=
thing at all,=E2=80=9D Martinez added, referring to Oscar de la Renta, Narc=
iso Rodriguez and Carolina Herrera =E2=80=94 Americans of, respectively, Do=
minican, Cuban and Venezuelan ancestry. And before Chavarria, there wasn=E2=
=80=99t anything at the commercial or street level to speak to the complexi=
ties of a Latino population that Census Bureau figures put at more than 60 =
million, a group that defies any attempt to reduce or define it according t=
o monolithic stereotypes.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CThe potential effect of having someone who understands all of o=
ur dualities at a label as influential as Calvin is just incredible,=E2=80=
=9D Martinez said.</p>
<p>Jess Lomax, the creative director for global design at Calvin Klein, was=
 a senior creative director at Nike before she was named in late 2020 to he=
lp right a listing corporate behemoth. =E2=80=9CWilly was an obvious hire, =
one of the very first additions I made,=E2=80=9D Lomax said.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d followed him for some time,=E2=80=9D she added, cit=
ing among his many strengths Chavarria=E2=80=99s solid formalism, adventuro=
us play with proportion, rootedness in his own culture and lifelong embrace=
 of diversity in all its dispersions.</p>
<p>As much as anything, it was his democratic vision of fashion that attrac=
ted her to Chavarria, said Lomax, who is seeking to radically recast the co=
rporate vision of a premier American label, one that somehow lost its way u=
nder the direction of Belgian designer Raf Simons.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CBeauty, cultural relevance, how a product connects to a custome=
r =E2=80=94 all of that is so, so important,=E2=80=9D Lomax said. =E2=80=9C=
Willy brings all of that.=E2=80=9D
</p><p>
Case in point: Chavarria=E2=80=99s quiet role in devising Kanye West=E2=80=
=99s Yeezy Gap collaboration, created over a two-year period during which, =
despite the travel restrictions imposed by the COVID-19 virus, Chavarria co=
mmuted regularly from Copenhagen, where he lives with his husband, David Ra=
mirez, a vice president at the Danish Pandora jewelry company, to West=E2=
=80=99s ranch in Cody, Wyoming, and his compound in Calabasas, California.<=
/p>
<p>Though Chavarria is tight-lipped about what part he played in forming th=
e collection, referring to himself modestly as a =E2=80=9Cconsultant,=E2=80=
=9D anyone familiar with his work can detect his hand in designs like the c=
ollarless $200 =E2=80=9Cround jacket=E2=80=9D puffer West teased on Instagr=
am in June and that sold out so quickly that examples are now being offered=
 for as much as $1,500 on Grailed and other websites.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9COne of the genius gifts Kanye has is that he is constantly scou=
ring the world for talent,=E2=80=9D said Chavarria, whom West contacted in =
2018 after spotting a review of a Chavarria show at New York Fashion Week: =
Men=E2=80=99s that the designer had staged in the beer-scented hallways and=
 backrooms of the venerable gay leather bar, the Eagle, which opened for bu=
siness in 1970.</p>
<p>
As in prior shows that overtly explored themes of immigration, gender dysph=
oria, ableism and other hot-button issues, Chavarria fused dimensions of hi=
s own cultural experience growing up in California to those of fragile, if =
historically disfavored, subcultures like gay practitioners of BDSM.</p>
<p>Taking aspects of =E2=80=9Clowrider style,=E2=80=9D like crisp oversize =
shirts, their shoulders dropped and ornamented with ruching; or skirt-wide =
khakis he termed =E2=80=9Ccholo pants=E2=80=9D and then cinched with karate=
 obis; or tracksuits with satin inlays shown under studded biker jackets an=
d accessorized with gnarly studded belts or leather Muir caps no self-respe=
cting leather daddy would be seen without, he produced results that were as=
 starkly beautiful as they were original and unexpected.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CI wanted to use from my past the beautiful things that emerged =
when I was growing up around Chicano culture,=E2=80=9D Chavarria said then.=
 He seamlessly married those tropes to stylistic elements of a scene he may=
 never have participated in but had long admired from afar.
</p><p>
Chavarria cast that show, titled =E2=80=9CCruising,=E2=80=9D as he has each=
 successive one since he incorporated, with an array of models drawn both f=
rom inside the industry and far outside its customary reach. Take a casting=
 for his next show, =E2=80=9CCut Deep,=E2=80=9D which was inspired by deliv=
ery men, he said, and is set to take place Sept. 8 at a storied barbershop =
on Astor Place.</p>
<p>For this show he instructed his casting director, Brent Chua, to send ou=
t a call for young guys with, yes, agency representation, but also ordinary=
 types with the sort of everyday beauty few bother to notice because, as Ch=
avarria said, =E2=80=9Cnobody bothers to look up at the DoorDash guy.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99d been in the business so long before I went out on m=
y own that the point became not so much seeing how much volume you could se=
ll, but how much beauty you could create,=E2=80=9D said Chavarria, whose Jo=
e Boxer days were governed by sales goals rather far more than design. =E2=
=80=9CIt was how many banana print boxers do we need to sell.</p>
<p>
That he intends, at his own label and at Calvin Klein, to build something c=
ulturally reparative could be sensed from the responses of the hopefuls tha=
t turned up for the casting: construction workers and musicians and street-=
scouted newcomers, few of whom had considered themselves beautiful, let alo=
ne marketable to the restrictive sphere of fashion, as it turned out.</p>
<p>They were men like Elias Priddie, 24, a soulful-looking day-laborer and =
sometime bare-knuckle boxer from the Bronx, who =E2=80=9Cnever even thought=
 I could be good-looking,=E2=80=9D as he explained. They were men like Chac=
hi Martinez, 28, one of Chavarria=E2=80=99s designated muses, =E2=80=9Ca to=
tal sweetheart, though he does look kind of scary,=E2=80=9D as the designer=
 said, owing to Martinez=E2=80=99s abundant SoCal gang-style tattoos.</p>
<p>Or they were lanky types like Antonio Macek, 20, a longhaired former ama=
teur hurdler of Black and Czech ancestry who had grown up being termed eith=
er too pretty or plain ugly or told he was weird. =E2=80=9CI was looked at =
as different because I didn=E2=80=99t look like a normal person,=E2=80=9D M=
acek said.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CThere are so many ways in this world in which we are kept, or w=
e keep ourselves, from being beautiful,=E2=80=9D said Chavarria, who has he=
ld onto a SoHo apartment, as much as anything for its easy access to Tompki=
ns Square Park in the East Village, one of the last bastions, in a fast-hom=
ogenizing city, of racial and gender diversity.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s this really damaging loss of psychic and even p=
hysical territory if the culture never gives you any confirmation of your t=
ype of beauty,=E2=80=9D Chavarria said.</p>
<p>Imagine, said Corey Stokes, the fashion director of Highsnobiety, that o=
ne=E2=80=99s daily experience resembled that of Macek, the ex-athlete told =
all his life he looked strange. =E2=80=9CI get chills when I think about be=
ing in the most impressionable years of your life and not being represented=
,=E2=80=9D Stokes said. =E2=80=9CNot thinking of yourself as anyone=E2=80=
=99s idea of beauty: think how that shapes the way you see yourself and you=
r entire future.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>Steven Kolb, the CEO of the Council of Fashion Designers of America, rec=
alls that when he was introduced to Chavarria, he was first struck by his e=
xperience with other commercial brands, an important element in a field tha=
t tends to attract creative people with no business experience. It was only=
 after Kolb invited the designer to show under the CFDA=E2=80=99s big tent =
in 2015, soon after Chavarria went into business for himself, that he under=
stood his true mettle.</p>
<p>Kolb=E2=80=99s decision was to prove controversial, as he soon found, wh=
en the designer mounted shows featuring models of all genders or none in pa=
rticular, well before such castings had become routine industry practice; s=
howed his work on models in cages built to symbolize the plight of border d=
etainees; and cast immigrants without legal status to walk the runway in hi=
s shows.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CWhat struck me, though, was that Willy=E2=80=99s commitment to =
culture and cause or purpose was equally or if not of greater importance to=
 him than commercial success,=E2=80=9D Kolb said. =E2=80=9CHis purpose is s=
tanding for something beside the clothes. Sometimes when you hear that from=
 designers, it doesn=E2=80=99t feel authentic. It feels like marketing. But=
 that is not the case with him.=E2=80=9D
</p><p>
This above all is why having someone like Chavarria step into =E2=80=9Csuch=
 a huge role=E2=80=9D at one of the most widely distributed and potentially=
 influential labels in the world is so significant, Stokes explained.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CIt is a giant step in the direction of making sure that people =
are seen. That is a huge thing, though keep in mind it=E2=80=99s not the on=
ly thing. Consumers don=E2=80=99t only want to be =E2=80=98seen=E2=80=99 in=
 some marketing sense. They want to feel as if they are actually being cons=
idered.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>
The ability to deliver on that notion is what Chavarria found most =E2=80=
=9Cmagical=E2=80=9D about being offered a top job at Calvin Klein. =E2=80=
=9CWhen you think about how Calvin Klein succeeded, what was it?=E2=80=9D h=
e said. =E2=80=9CSure, he made sales, but his real genius was understanding=
 image and how to include people in something that took them beyond themsel=
ves.=E2=80=9D
This article originally appeared in The New York Times.
