<p>This generation of women had achieved what no other had. They were part =
of a monumental shift in the roles women could play in American society tha=
t began in the late 1970s and continues today =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cthe quiet =
revolution,=E2=80=9D economist Claudia Goldin calls it. In 1955, women were=
 one-third of the U.S. the labor force =E2=80=94 they were unlikely to atte=
nd college, and if they worked, they were expected to be teachers or secret=
aries. That share slowly expanded until, in January 2019, women achieved a =
milestone: They made up more of the workforce than men.</p>
<p>The pandemic erased that progress in a matter of weeks, and just as it t=
ook decades to achieve, it could take years to regain. Last spring, 5.1 mil=
lion U.S. mothers of young children stopped working for pay. Today, 1.3 mil=
lion of them are out of work. Now, 56% of American women are working for pa=
y, the lowest level since 1986.</p>
<p>When the pandemic created a child care crisis, mothers became the defaul=
t solution. Even as society starts to reopen, many feel forgotten. Child ca=
re, education and other aspects of daily life remain disrupted because youn=
g children cannot yet be vaccinated; and government paid-leave programs hav=
e expired.</p>
<p>Interviews with 15 mothers in one place, Los Angeles County, reveal the =
costs when society relies on mothers to be the backup plan. For mothers who=
 have had to stop working, it=E2=80=99s been more than the loss of a payche=
ck. It=E2=80=99s a loss of self-determination, of self-reliance, of complex=
 selves. No matter the jobs they held, the education they had or the backgr=
ounds they came from, they described a loss of identity apart from being a =
mother.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CMen who are out of work are still presumed to be workers, but w=
omen aren=E2=80=99t, because we frame work for women as a choice,=E2=80=9D =
said Sarah Damaske, a sociologist at Pennsylvania State University whose bo=
ok, =E2=80=9CThe Tolls of Uncertainty,=E2=80=9D published this month, is ab=
out how unemployed Americans=E2=80=99 experiences are shaped by gender and =
class. =E2=80=9CSo when they unexpectedly lose a job in a society in which =
their working was in question all the time, it really throws how they=E2=80=
=99re thinking about who they are into question.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>Women have more options now for what to do with their lives =E2=80=94 bu=
t that also means that whether they work for pay or stay home with children=
 is often considered a personal choice. What=E2=80=99s happened to America=
=E2=80=99s working mothers in the last year is the story of what happens wh=
en any choices they once had disappeared.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not: =E2=80=98I had to make a choice.=E2=80=99 The=
 choice was made for me and a million other people,=E2=80=9D said Joy Meule=
nberg, 37, after her dog-walking business and acting auditions dwindled and=
 her daughter=E2=80=99s school closed.</p>
<p>Leah Duenas Torres, 37, who lost her sales job, had been the first in he=
r family to go to college. She earned a master=E2=80=99s degree and support=
ed her husband and family as he attended medical school. Then, instead of b=
eing the =E2=80=9Cfun mom,=E2=80=9D she became =E2=80=9Cthe enforcer,=E2=80=
=9D helping Santino, who is 7 and has autism, and Phoenix, 5, attend online=
 school.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CI wasn=E2=80=99t a stay-at-home mom, and now I=E2=80=99m not a =
breadwinner,=E2=80=9D said Torres, who is expecting a baby this spring. =E2=
=80=9CI haven=E2=80=99t even said out loud any aspirations. I don=E2=80=99t=
 know what I=E2=80=99m going to do with my life anymore besides be a mom.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CI appreciate Zoloft more now than ever,=E2=80=9D she said.</p>
<p>Marina Bonilla, 40, lost her job as a hotel housekeeper when the pandemi=
c began. A single mother, she immigrated to the United States from El Salva=
dor to find a better life for her daughter, Genesis, 4. Central to that was=
 earning a living: =E2=80=9CI was used to going to work and making money to=
 buy the necessities for me and my daughter,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CI =
wanted to cry.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>She was grateful for having more time with Genesis, but this spring, whe=
n she found a job as a hospital housekeeper, it felt like relief: =E2=80=9C=
I thank God that he gave me the strength to go on.=E2=80=9D
</p><p>
Women on the opposite end of the income spectrum also grieved their loss of=
 agency. One month before the world shut down, Jenna Lecce Streit, 48, an a=
cupuncturist, found a space to open her own practice. She had taken time of=
f work before her son, Sidney, 8, entered school, and was reveling in being=
 back.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CIt was time for me to be my own independent person, to really d=
ive into my career,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CIt was like, oh my gosh, I=
=E2=80=99m finally there. I=E2=80=99m 48 years old and I=E2=80=99m finally =
there.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>Now, she=E2=80=99s overseeing Sidney=E2=80=99s remote school from their =
vacation home in Mazatl=C3=A1n, Mexico. Her husband regularly travels for w=
ork as a reality TV producer, and has become a COVID compliance officer for=
 film sets, so his career has =E2=80=9Cblossomed,=E2=80=9D she said.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CI literally am bloated when I=E2=80=99m not working because my =
chi isn=E2=80=99t flowing,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CI know it=E2=80=99s =
a very L.A. thing to say. But it=E2=80=99s really brought to the forefront =
the paradox of being a working woman who is a wife and mother. The paradox =
is so screaming bright shining in my face right now. I love everything abou=
t motherhood, and yet it doesn=E2=80=99t feel fair that I should have to sa=
crifice my career.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CI guess what I=E2=80=99m missing is that thing that=E2=80=99s m=
ine, and what that is is the little piece of my identity that=E2=80=99s my =
career.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>
<b> Loss of Choice </b>
</p>
<p>Of the 1.3 million mothers living with babies, toddlers or school-age ch=
ildren who are no longer working for pay, some are on leave from their jobs=
, some are looking for work and others have given up for now, according to =
census data.</p>
<p>Since late fall, more mothers living with school-age children have retur=
ned to work, almost catching up with fathers, but mothers=E2=80=99 return t=
o work has stalled. The number of mothers living with preschool or school-a=
ged children who are actively working is down 4%, about the same as adults =
without children at home, though their reasons for being out of work are ve=
ry different.</p>
<p>A new survey by Morning Consult for The New York Times =E2=80=94 of a re=
presentative group of 1,001 mothers nationwide who were working for pay bef=
ore the pandemic began, including 448 who quit =E2=80=94 found that 60% of =
those who quit were satisfied with their decision. Another 20% had consider=
ed quitting for child care reasons. But that doesn=E2=80=99t mean it=E2=80=
=99s what they would have chosen if they had options. Eighty percent said t=
hey were the only parent who considered quitting =E2=80=94 their partner di=
d not.</p>
<p>Employment fell more sharply for those without college educations or hig=
h incomes; for those whose jobs couldn=E2=80=99t be done from home; and for=
 those who are Black or Latina. But the biggest difference between mothers =
who kept working and didn=E2=80=99t, the survey found, was simply whether t=
heir children=E2=80=99s schools were open.</p>
<p>Nationwide, just over half of districts are offering full-time, in-perso=
n learning, and an additional one-fifth are open part time. Los Angeles pub=
lic schools reopened last month, some for three hours a day, and 55% of ele=
mentary students have returned.</p>
<p>Fathers, grandparents and others have left the workforce, too. In famili=
es in which fathers did more of the pandemic child care, mothers were more =
likely to stay employed, research shows.</p>
<p>But in most cases, it has been mothers who cut back on paid work for chi=
ld care. Of fathers living with their children, 600,000 are still out of wo=
rk, though they are much less likely to have left for child care reasons, t=
he census analysis shows.</p>
<p>Jennifer Park Zerkel, 42, who had started a tutoring business, said: =E2=
=80=9CIf I didn=E2=80=99t have kids, I=E2=80=99d be down there, I=E2=80=99d=
 be full on trying to get my business back up. But who=E2=80=99s going to t=
ake care of my kids?=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>Her husband often works long hours, but even when he doesn=E2=80=99t, he=
 keeps his own schedule. =E2=80=9CI am the primary parent,=E2=80=9D she sai=
d.
</p><p>
There are many reasons that mothers are the default caregivers, beginning w=
ith centuries of tradition. They are also generally paid less than their hu=
sbands. But this is a vicious cycle: The gender pay gap starts when women b=
ecome mothers =E2=80=94 because they spend more time than men on child care=
, or employers assume they will. Then, when one parent has to step back fro=
m paid work for caregiving, mothers do because they earn less, reinforcing =
the pattern.</p>
<p>The U.S. economy rewards undivided loyalty. Salaried employees who work =
long hours are paid disproportionately more, and many hourly workers are ex=
pected to be available on a moment=E2=80=99s notice. Part-time work, at lea=
st the kind offering decent pay and employee benefits, isn=E2=80=99t widely=
 available, and the United States is the only industrialized nation that do=
esn=E2=80=99t mandate paid family leave. (For the first time, Congress pass=
ed 12 weeks of paid caregiving leave during the pandemic, but it expired at=
 the end of 2020.)</p>
<p>
=E2=80=9CWe think we=E2=80=99ve progressed so much, and then this pandemic =
happens and we all just revert back to these traditional behaviors,=E2=80=
=9D said Misty L. Heggeness, a principal economist at the Census Bureau. =
=E2=80=9CAnd this is a good moment to reflect, why do we do that?=E2=80=9D<=
/p>
<p>Delia Hauser, 40, a costumer and artist, had a thriving freelance career=
 she had built from the garage she converted to an office. Now, the office =
is used by her husband, a creative director. She is in the house, caring fo=
r sons George, 7, who has a rare disability and needs help for his Zoom mee=
tings, and Fred, 4, when he is not in preschool.</p>
<p>There was never a thought that her husband would be the one to stop work=
ing. =E2=80=9CHe makes way more money than I probably ever could,=E2=80=9D =
she said. =E2=80=9CBut also, I was already very much in charge of George=E2=
=80=99s world. The expectation is just always on us to give up things. No o=
ne even has to say it. It just is.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p><b> Loss of Self-Reliance </b>
</p>
<p>Mothers across the income and career spectrum described devotion to the =
jobs they had.</p>
<p>Ana Recinos, 32, had worked several jobs at once since she was 18. When =
her daughter Josephine=E2=80=99s school closed, she quit her full-time jobs=
, as a waitress and at Target, while her wife continued working in retail. =
Now she spends her days caring for Josephine, 10, and researching food bank=
s.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CI feel like I let my family down,=E2=80=9D she said.</p>
<p>Damaske, from Penn State, said that in her research, low-wage women had =
stronger attachments to work because of the effort it took to arrange adequ=
ate child care. =E2=80=9CResearchers and the public alike can look at low-w=
age workers and not see the effort that goes into keeping and doing those j=
obs, especially for women with kids,=E2=80=9D she said.</p>
<p>For many mothers, losing work felt like losing their independence.</p>
<p>Guadalupe Villegas had been homeless but had regained custody of her chi=
ldren, and was working two jobs as a prep cook. Those jobs disappeared with=
 the shutdowns, and her biggest fear is losing her children again. Now she =
is caring for her children and her mother, who was found to have cancer las=
t year.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CI am an overloaded ship right now,=E2=80=9D she said.</p>
<p>Da=E2=80=99Chante Bowers, 28, had also been on a path out of poverty. Th=
e single mother of Victory, 4, Bowers was attending community college.</p>
<p>Last fall, she was accepted to the University of California, Irvine, her=
 =E2=80=9Cdream school.=E2=80=9D But three weeks into the semester, she had=
 to drop out =E2=80=94 Victory was too young to attend preschool online.</p=
>
<p>They live on county aid, =E2=80=9Cand that is not enough to feed a Fifi =
bird.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>Victory=E2=80=99s father is not around. Bowers re-enrolled this spring, =
and her father helps watch Victory when she has class.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CBeing on the path I wanted to be on, I=E2=80=99ve worked so har=
d to get there, and for it to come to such a halt, it=E2=80=99s mind-boggli=
ng,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CI think that=E2=80=99s the best way I could=
 describe it without getting too emotional.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p><b> Loss of a Worker=E2=80=99s Purpose </b>
</p>
<p>Working mothers=E2=80=99 dual identities have always affected their care=
ers. In a study in which researchers sent out fake r=C3=A9sum=C3=A9s =E2=80=
=94 identical except for a line about being a member of the PTA =E2=80=94 p=
arents were less likely to get interviews. Mothers receive less pay and few=
er promotions. Workers who ask for flexibility for family reasons are often=
 penalized; those who hide the reason are not.</p>
<p>The pandemic made it impossible for parents to hide that part of their i=
dentity at work.
</p><p>
Marisa Smith, 40, who worked as a business manager, was the only person in =
her office who was furloughed =E2=80=94 and the only parent. Shortly after =
she returned, someone at her 6-year-old son Kai=E2=80=99s day care contract=
ed the coronavirus, so she had to stay home with him to quarantine. After t=
hat, she was laid off.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CI have to kind of wonder if it was because I had a son,=E2=80=
=9D said Smith, who is divorced from Kai=E2=80=99s father.</p>
<p>She applied for jobs for months before she found a new business manager =
role. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s hard to feel good about yourself when you=E2=80=
=99re not feeling like a productive person in society,=E2=80=9D she said.</=
p>
<p>
Many American women have carefully planned their working lives to accommoda=
te children. They choose jobs with more flexibility or fewer hours, even if=
 they earn less or are overqualified, or start businesses so they can contr=
ol their schedules. The new survey found that self-employed women were much=
 more likely to quit in the pandemic.</p>
<p>Lola Keyes Wood had co-founded a Hollywood travel and event company, now=
 closed with no plans to reopen. Her husband, founder of a consulting compa=
ny, has continued to work, often traveling. To get help with their children=
, Hendrix, 6, and Lenox, 2, Wood decamped to her parents=E2=80=99 house in =
Virginia.</p>
<p>Her children are too young to do remote school without help. The 30 hour=
s a week she worked pre-pandemic is now 10 if she=E2=80=99s lucky. She work=
s on business ideas 2 1/2 hours a day while Lenox goes to a play group.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CEven with the help of a babysitter, laundry piles up, the kitch=
en=E2=80=99s dirty,=E2=80=9D she said. =E2=80=9CWhen do you open your bills=
? Did you respond to the stuff that came in the mail? No, I did not, becaus=
e I only have 2 1/2 hours a day.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p><b> Loss of a Mother=E2=80=99s Confidence </b>
</p>
<p>Even in normal times, American mothers, more than those in other rich co=
untries, describe feeling guilty and stressed. The pandemic seemed to sharp=
en that self-doubt.
</p><p>
Meulenberg, the dog walker, and her husband, a set dresser, had taken turns=
 being the primary earner. When the pandemic began, he was earning more, so=
 she took over the care of their 5-year-old daughter, Madeleine. She=E2=80=
=99s grateful her husband has work, but feels her life is on hold: =E2=80=
=9CI=E2=80=99m not a housewife person.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p></p>
<p>The pandemic sent many working mothers into crisis mode, and they did wh=
at they have always done =E2=80=94 cared for their children when they neede=
d it.</p>
<p>
Now, with vaccines available for those 12 and older and with more schools o=
pen, the mothers in Los Angeles said they still couldn=E2=80=99t see the fu=
ture =E2=80=94 school and camp schedules aren=E2=80=99t back to normal, and=
 some didn=E2=80=99t feel school was safe yet =E2=80=94 but they could begi=
n to contemplate it.</p>
<p>In the national survey, 70% of mothers who had quit said they planned to=
 return to paid work. Fifteen percent didn=E2=80=99t know, and the same sha=
re didn=E2=80=99t plan to return. But American workplaces frown on gaps in =
r=C3=A9sum=C3=A9s, especially for women doing caregiving.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CThis isn=E2=80=99t just career women climbing the ladder and ge=
tting pushed down two rungs,=E2=80=9D said Goldin, the economist. =E2=80=9C=
I am very, very concerned about women working in sectors that have been imp=
loded and probably won=E2=80=99t come back anywhere near where they were.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>There are things that could help, starting with fully opening schools an=
d child care centers. Incentives like tax credits could encourage companies=
 to rehire mothers. Job search and retraining programs could help workers f=
ind jobs outside the service industry. Longer term, researchers say, the pr=
edicament could be blunted with policies like paid sick and family leave, a=
ffordable child care and financial support for unpaid caregivers.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CThis offers the opportunity to really reimagine how things can =
operate differently,=E2=80=9D said Michelle Rhone-Collins, chief executive =
of Lift, a nonprofit that helps mothers and children living in poverty.</p>
<p>For their part, the women interviewed in Los Angeles County said they we=
re determined to make their way back to paid work. Some were grateful for t=
he detour.</p>
<p>Wood, who closed her events business, said the pandemic gave her the fir=
st chance since graduate school to pause and evaluate her career. She is st=
arting a new business, inspired by her children =E2=80=94 a line of pajamas=
 with Black Santa that she wants to expand.</p>
<p>April Williams, 40, who was laid off after achieving her dream promotion=
, is also starting a business. Her son Zell, 9, has made her a =E2=80=9Cbas=
ketball mom,=E2=80=9D and she=E2=80=99s planning to open a high-end gym in =
their neighborhood.</p>
<p>Hauser, the costume designer, is considering becoming a disability advoc=
ate, using the experiences she has had helping her son. Recinos, so accusto=
med to working two full-time jobs, has started an online training course to=
 become a medical assistant.</p>
<p>Zerkel, who started the tutoring business, wants to open a preschool as =
well. Villegas is trying to get certification as a home health aide, the jo=
b she has been doing for her mother.</p>
<p>If Bowers finishes college, she plans to use her education to become a s=
ocial worker: =E2=80=9CI want to be able to help people, give people a pers=
on to relate to, to know that they can make it through anything.=E2=80=9D
</p>

