<p>NEW YORK =E2=80=94 Hop Kee is a basement Cantonese eatery offering $9.50=
 shrimp lo mein. Hwa Yuan Szechuan is a three-story, white-tablecloth resta=
urant where the whole fish with hot bean sauce is $45.</p>
<p>Both have long histories in Manhattan=E2=80=99s Chinatown, and a deep av=
ersion to delivery apps.</p>
<p>Hop Kee=E2=80=99s owner could not afford the services=E2=80=99 high fees=
. Hwa Yuan=E2=80=99s owner, Chen Lieh Tang, 67, said his cuisine was meant =
to be eaten in one place: Hwa Yuan. =E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t want people to=
 eat the food cold,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not my style.=
=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>So when the coronavirus pandemic shut down all on-site dining, almost no=
 one was able to enjoy their food, forcing them to confront difficult quest=
ions about modernization and adaptation that may reshape businesses across =
the storied neighborhood.</p>
<p>Since its formation around the 1870s, Chinatown has managed to preserve =
its working-class immigrant character, even as wealth transformed nearly ev=
ery neighborhood around it.</p>
<p>But some of the traditions that kept Chinatown rooted to its history hav=
e made it one of the neighborhoods most heavily scarred by the pandemic. No=
w, the economic suffering has intensified a long-simmering generational div=
ide, between younger people who believe Chinatown must get with the times t=
o survive, and older ones who worry about it becoming a theme park of Insta=
grammable desserts and $18 Asian-fusion cocktails.</p>
<p>Chinatown had already seen sharp declines in foot traffic by Lunar New Y=
ear in January, typically its busiest season, because of anti-Chinese xenop=
hobia linked to the virus and because of a slowdown in tourism. When the ci=
ty shut down in March and customers largely stayed home, old-school Chinato=
wn shops were particularly exposed.</p>
<p>Many could not rely on deliveries or curbside pickups, the only transact=
ions permitted for businesses in recent months. (On June 22, the city began=
 allowing limited in-store shopping, as well as outdoor dining, which is a =
rarity in Chinatown.) Only 38% of storefronts in Chinatown had an online pr=
esence, compared with more than 70% in wealthier neighborhoods like the Wes=
t Village, according to an analysis by Live XYZ, a mapping tech company.</p=
>
<p>Nearly a third of Chinatown restaurants are cash-only, according to data=
 from the review site Yelp, and most shunned delivery apps because of their=
 fees. They were accustomed to a business model reliant on high-volume, low=
-priced dishes like $7 noodle soups served to local residents and workers.<=
/p>
<p>Some businesses like Hop Kee, which has been owned by the same family fo=
r five decades, are holding the line.</p>
<p>The restaurant=E2=80=99s cash register and waiters=E2=80=99 uniforms hav=
e stayed the same since the 1970s. Hop Kee doesn=E2=80=99t take credit card=
s.</p>
<p>Before the pandemic, it would be packed to capacity with 160 diners on a=
 Saturday night. Now it serves about 20 takeout orders a day for diners who=
 order in person or call Hop Kee=E2=80=99s phone number.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not about making money if you=E2=80=99re here for =
the long term,=E2=80=9D said the owner, Peter Lee, 56. =E2=80=9CIf you go o=
ld-school style, people will look at you like, there=E2=80=99s more truth t=
o this. There=E2=80=99s no sense of authenticity in the digital world.=E2=
=80=9D</p>
<p>Other restaurants, including Hwa Yuan, are embracing the iPhone age, usu=
ally at the urging of younger generations.</p>
<p>Hwa Yuan has a special place in this country=E2=80=99s culinary history:=
 Tang=E2=80=99s father was revered as the chef who introduced Americans to =
cold sesame noodles.</p>
<p>After the shutdown, Tang=E2=80=99s son, James, 35, insisted that the res=
taurant sign up for apps. Now Hwa Yuan can be ordered via Grubhub and DoorD=
ash.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CWe basically had to twist his arm,=E2=80=9D said James Tang, an=
 investment banker. The restaurant has suffered $1 million in losses, but, =
the elder Tang said, =E2=80=9Cat least there=E2=80=99s hope.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>All kinds of Chinatown businesses have been facing similar choices. Foot=
 traffic was slow at Po Wing Hong, a specialty grocery with a focus on drie=
d seafood and Chinese herbs, so Sophia Ng Tsao, 37, has persuaded her paren=
ts, who opened the business in 1980, to start an online store.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s important to diversify your customer base, getting=
 that younger customer, but we=E2=80=99ll do it slowly and organically,=E2=
=80=9D Tsao said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a struggle for any multigenerationa=
l business.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>Before the virus, walking into parts of Chinatown was the rare Manhattan=
 experience of feeling transported to a place frozen in time. The sidewalks=
 overflowed with tourists and local shoppers crowding around street vendors=
 and seafood markets, a lively cacophony of sounds and smells.</p>
<p>At the pandemic=E2=80=99s peak in April, entire streets had become ghost=
 towns of metal shutters. When Phase 2 of the city=E2=80=99s reopening bega=
n on June 22, only about half of the 46 businesses on a three-block stretch=
 of Mott Street, the heart of Chinatown, were open. Barbershops offering $9=
 haircuts had long lines, while other stores had darkened interiors and emp=
loyees lingering at their entrances.</p>
<p>Many businesses were unable to avail themselves of emergency, government=
-backed loans because of delays caused by an initial lack of translation of=
 the paperwork, and because some businesses only keep accounting records on=
 paper, according to community advocates.</p>
<p>Longtime residents say they understand when businesses try to survive by=
 diversifying their clientele, especially if those customers explore other =
stores in the area. But they also worry about trendier establishments turni=
ng the neighborhood into a caricature of Chinatown.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CThey do attract a crowd that=E2=80=99s less respectful of the c=
ulture or don=E2=80=99t appreciate it,=E2=80=9D said Geoff Lee, 68, a lifel=
ong Chinatown resident. =E2=80=9CThey look at Chinatown more as a novelty t=
han a true identity.=E2=80=9D
</p><p>
Perhaps no other business has been as boundary-pushing, and controversial t=
o neighborhood stalwarts, as Nom Wah Tea Parlor, which opened in 1920 and w=
as taken over by the previous owner=E2=80=99s nephew, Wilson Tang, in 2011.=
</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve been told that I=E2=80=99m a sellout,=E2=80=9D Tan=
g, 41, said. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve also been told I=E2=80=99m a beacon of l=
ight.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>At Nom Wah, an order of four shrimp dumplings costs $6, twice the price =
at some other spots nearby. Before the pandemic, it was one of the few Chin=
atown restaurants on Caviar, a delivery app for upscale restaurants.</p>
<p>Nom Wah began selling frozen dumplings online during the pandemic, which=
 helped the business stay afloat this quarter, Wilson Tang said. He hopes t=
he coming release of his cookbook will provide a similar cushion in the fal=
l.</p>
<p>He said Chinatown businesses that can appeal to non-Asian customers are =
better equipped to weather the crisis.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CChange is inevitable,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIf you don=E2=
=80=99t morph and do better, you=E2=80=99re going to get left behind and di=
e.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>
There is no disagreement about the biggest threat to Chinatown: that busine=
sses could close for good. The ripple effects could force small-property ow=
ners to sell to corporate real estate firms that will increase rents and li=
kely bring in stores that offer nothing for immigrant residents.</p>
<p>Geoff Lee=E2=80=99s family has owned properties on Mott Street since the=
 1920s. One of the tenants, a beauty products store, has not paid rent in a=
t least three months, he said.</p>
<p>Developers have already been calling to ask if the family is willing to =
sell. (It is not, said Lee=E2=80=99s brother, Jan.) The neighborhood sits o=
n valuable real estate in Lower Manhattan, surrounded by the wealth of SoHo=
, TriBeCa and the Financial District.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re afraid that the pandemic makes that process of di=
splacement much easier to happen,=E2=80=9D said Jill Sung, 51, chief execut=
ive of Abacus Federal Savings Bank, a community bank whose oldest branch is=
 in Chinatown. =E2=80=9CWe don=E2=80=99t want things to disappear overnight=
. Where=E2=80=99s our history? It breaks that connection.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p>The neighborhood has already been losing its Chinese residents, even as =
the Chinese and Asian population has grown citywide, with many settling in =
the newer enclaves of Sunset Park, Brooklyn, and Flushing, Queens.</p>
<p>About 58% of Chinatown=E2=80=99s residents are Asian, according to the l=
atest five-year survey by the Census Bureau, down from about 69% in 2000.</=
p>
<p>Local businesses are also struggling with the prospect that the neighbor=
hood is becoming a retirement community. Among the Asians left in Chinatown=
, the only age group in which the population has increased is those who are=
 65 or older.</p>
<p>Adding another challenge for reopening, the neighborhood=E2=80=99s resta=
urant workers tend to be older and live far from Chinatown.</p>
<p>Jing Fong, an 800-seat dim sum hall, could not begin takeout orders duri=
ng the pandemic until this week, partly because many employees are in a hig=
her-risk age group and were unwilling to commute in, said Truman Lam, the r=
estaurant=E2=80=99s third-generation manager.</p>
<p>The staffing is also a reason the restaurant has struggled to update its=
 computer systems to, for instance, accept gift cards, Lam, 35, said. =E2=
=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s like teaching your parents how to use an iPhone,=E2=80=
=9D he said.
</p><p>
Kenneth Ma, 35, whose family has owned optical stores in Chinatown for four=
 decades, had pushed for the business to go cashless, but his family worrie=
d that the switch would drive away older neighbors who depended on them for=
 eye exams.</p>
<p>The stores, including Chinatown Optical and Mott Street Optical, have ma=
naged to straddle the old and the modern. They sell affordable metal glasse=
s alongside trendy plastic frames. Every employee speaks Mandarin, Cantones=
e and English.</p>
<p>Ma recently hired an expert in search engine optimization for Mott Stree=
t Optical=E2=80=99s website and is developing a way for customers to try on=
 glasses at home. His mother and uncle became open to these changes, he sai=
d, after the pandemic halted foot traffic from young professionals.</p>
<p>=E2=80=9CWe always ask, who are we for?=E2=80=9D Ma said. =E2=80=9CWe ar=
e for everybody that comes by Chinatown =E2=80=94 whoever lives here, eats =
here, stops by on the weekend. That=E2=80=99s always changing.=E2=80=9D
</p>

